        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "docs: add Superclaw DC control spine specs",
        "body": "## Summary\n- add Superclaw DC draft RFCs for control spine, tenant/isolation, Gateway to L5 identity, capability/PDP/ActionReceipt, and org-memory outbox\n- add machine-readable v0 contract schemas and fixtures\n- add runnable contract experiments for fail-closed behavior and schema validation\n\n## What Problem This Solves\nThe Superclaw DC architecture backlog had critical boundaries named but not pinned: `tenant_id` was overloaded, L5 channel identity could blur into canonical principal identity, root capability minting order conflicted with gateway checks, PDP cache invalidation was underspecified, platform delivery receipts were overloaded as audit receipts, and Mem0/provenance writes were described as one transaction without an implementation model.\n\nThis PR adds specs and contract artifacts that make those boundaries explicit before implementation starts.\n\n## Evidence\nLocal validation from the PR branch:\n\n```text\nnode docs/specs/superclaw-dc/experiments/contract-negative-tests.mjs\ncontract-negative-tests: 14 checks passed\n\nnode docs/specs/superclaw-dc/experiments/schema-validation.mjs\nschema-validation: 8 checks passed\n\npnpm docs:check-mdx\nDocs MDX check passed (687 files, 7671ms).\n```\n\nThe negative tests cover unsigned alias rejection, wrong cell/namespace/pool rejection, child capability scope/customer/expiry denial, stale PDP revocation epoch invalidation, memory provenance enforcement, ActionReceipt requirement, checkpoint context/capability validation, and erasure blocking stale reads.\n\n## Notes\nThis is a docs/specs PR. It intentionally pins contract vocabulary before implementation: no bare `tenant_id`; use customer tenant, org, isolation cell, namespace, runtime pool, and residency region separately.\n",
